":"1628–1667","1633–Male":"1633–Deceased","1600–Male":"1600–Deceased","1689":"1689","1667":"1667","1623":"1623","1600":"1600","1688":"1688","1633":"1633","1642":"1642","1620":"1620","22 APR 1633":"22 April 1633","1651":"1651","28 OCT 1623":"28 October 1623","1628":"1628","1658":"1658","Cheshunt,Hertford,England":"Cheshunt, Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom","Middlesex, England":"Middlesex, England","Hertford, Hertfordshire, England":"Hertford, Hertfordshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Crawley","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of the many places called Crawley, for example in Buckinghamshire, Essex, Hampshire, Sussex, and Oxfordshire, named with Old English <i>crāwe</i> ‘crow’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’. Compare   Crowley  .","Irish (Louth): in Ireland, this is generally the English name in 1 above, but it may also have been adopted for <b>McCrawley</b>, an Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Raghallaigh</b> ‘son of <i>Raghallach</i>’, also Anglicized as <b>Magreely</b>."],"variants":[{"name":"Crilly","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Liam.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Raghailligh</b> ‘son of <i>Raghailleach</i>’. Compare   Crawley  ."]},{"name":"Crowley","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Brennan, Kieran, Aileen, Assumpta, Bridie, Declan, Donovan, Kaitlin, Kevin Patrick, Maeve, Patrick Joseph.","Irish (Cork): Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Cruadhlaoich</b> ‘descendant of <i>Cruadhlaoch</i>’, a personal name composed of the elements <i>cruadh</i> ‘hardy’ + <i>laoch</i> ‘hero’. There has been some confusion with   Crawley  .","English: variant of   Crawley  ."]},{"name":"Craley","meanings":["Possibly an altered form of English   Crawley   (compare   Cralle  ). This surname is also found in England, but not before the early 17th century.","In some cases an Americanized form of Slovenian, Croatian, or Serbian   Kralj   ‘king’."]},{"name":"Creely","meanings":["Irish and Scottish (Dumfriesshire): alternative Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Raghallaigh</b> (see   Crawley  )."]},{"name":"Cralle","meanings":["Altered form of English   Crawley  .","Possibly also an Americanized form of German <b>Kralle</b> (see   Krall  )."]}]},{"name":"Izaac","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Biblical name, borne by the son of Abraham, who was nearly sacrificed by his father according to a command of God which was changed at the last moment. A ram, caught in a nearby thicket, was sacrificed instead (Genesis 22:1–13). Isaac lived on to marry Rebecca and become the father of Esau and Jacob. The derivation of the name is not certain; it has traditionally been connected with the Hebrew verb meaning ‘to laugh’. It was borne by both Christians and Jews in the Middle Ages and was taken up by the Puritans in the 16th century."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705210,"age":0,"year":"1600","julianDay":2305448,"title":"The Honourable East India Company","description":"The Honourable East India Company, a British joint-stock company, was established in 1600 for trade in the Indian Ocean region. At its height, the British East India Company had a private army which was twice the size of the British Army, ruled large sections of India, and revenues in the millions.","url":"https://www.historic-uk.com/HistoryUK/HistoryofEngland/The-East-India-Company/","urlTitle":"Historic UK - The East India Company","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705212,"age":20,"year":"1620","julianDay":2312753,"title":"The Pilgrims Board the Mayflower","description":"\"The Pilgrims boarded the Mayflower in search of religious freedom in the New World in September 1620. The Mayflower set sail from Plymouth, England, with 102 passengers, 40 of whom called themselves \"\"Saints.\"\" After two stormy months at sea, the ship reached the New World. Nearly half of the group died during their first winter due to malnutrition and the harsh New England winter.\"","url":"https://www.themayflowersociety.org/the-pilgrims/pilgrim-history","urlTitle":"The Mayflower Society - Pilgrim History","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705213,"age":42,"year":"1642","toYear":"1651","julianDay":2320789,"title":"The English Civil War","description":"A series of conflicts regarding England's governance during the years 1642 to 1651 is now known as The English Civil War. Charles I summoned supporters to join him against his enemies in Parliament. In October 1642, nearly 10,000 men fought for Charles I and chased Parliament across the River Tamar. Fighting continued for years and was finally ended at the Battle of Worcester on September 3, 1651, with a Parliamentarian victory.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705216,"age":88,"year":"1688","toYear":"1689","julianDay":2337590,"title":"Glorious Revolution","description":"The Glorious Revolution brought the downfall of Catholic King James II and the reign of his Protestant daughter Mary and her Dutch husband, William III of Orange.","url":"http://www.bbc.co.uk/history/british/civil_war_revolution/glorious_revolution_01.shtml","urlTitle":"BBC - Glorious Revolution","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Izaac Crawley was born in 1600, in Hertford, Hertfordshire, England. He had at least 1 son and 2 daughters with Elizabeth Sawyer."},"et":{"1600–":"1600–Surnud","1600–1658":"1600–1658","1623–Female":"1623–Surnud","1628–1667":"1628–1667","1633–Male":"1633–Surnud","1600–Male":"1600–Surnud","1689":"1689","1667":"1667","1623":"1623","1600":"1600","1688":"1688","1633":"1633","1642":"1642","1620":"1620","22 APR 1633":"22. aprill 1633","1651":"1651","28 OCT 1623":"28. oktoober 1623","1628":"1628","1658":"1658","Cheshunt,Hertford,England":"Cheshunt, Hertfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Middlesex, England":"Middlesex, England","Hertford, Hertfordshire, England":"Hertford, 